  "prompt": "What is the procedure to apply for a passport?",
  "response": "The procedure to apply for a passport depends on whether you're applying for the first time, renewing, replacing a lost or stolen passport, or correcting a mistake. Here's a general overview, with specifics for each case:\n\n**General Steps (Most Applications):**\n\n1.  **Determine Eligibility:**  Make sure you are a U.S. citizen. You'll need to provide proof.\n\n2.  **Complete the Application Form:** There are different forms depending on your situation:\n\n    *   **Form DS-11: Application for a U.S. Passport:**  Used for:\n        *   First-time applicants\n        *   Applicants under 16\n        *   Applicants whose previous passport was lost, stolen, or damaged\n        *   Applicants whose previous passport was issued more than 15 years ago\n        *   Applicants whose name has changed since their passport was issued\n    *   **Form DS-82: Application for a U.S. Passport Renewal:** Used for renewals if you meet *all* of these conditions:\n        *   Your previous passport was issued when you were 16 or older\n        *   Your previous passport was issued within the last 15 years\n        *   Your previous passport is undamaged\n        *   Your name is the same, or you can legally document your name change with your renewal application\n    *   **Form DS-5504: Application for a U.S. Passport - Name Change, Data Correction, and Limited Passport Book Replacement:**  Used to correct errors, change your name within one year of passport issuance, or replace a limited-validity passport.\n\n    *   **Where to find the forms:** Download the forms from the U.S. Department of State's website:  travel.state.gov\n\n    *   **Filling out the form:**\n        *   Read the instructions carefully.\n        *   Use black ink.\n        *   Print clearly.\n        *   Answer all questions truthfully.\n        *   Don't sign the form until instructed to do so by an acceptance agent (if required).\n\n3.  **Gather Supporting Documentation:** The required documents vary depending on the form you are using.  Expect to need the following:\n\n    *   **Proof of U.S. Citizenship:** (original *or* certified copy)\n        *   Birth certificate issued by a U.S. city, county, or state (must have a raised seal)\n        *   Certificate of Citizenship\n        *   Certificate of Naturalization\n        *   Consular Report of Birth Abroad (CRBA)\n        *   Previous, undamaged U.S. passport (for renewals)\n    *   **Proof of Identity:** (original *and* photocopy)\n        *   Valid driver's license\n        *   Valid state-issued ID card\n        *   Valid U.S. military ID\n        *   Valid U.S. government employee ID\n        *   Previous U.S. passport\n        *   For applicants under 16, parent(s)' or legal guardian(s)' identification may be required.\n    *   **Photocopies of Citizenship and Identity Documents:** Photocopying tips:\n        *   Photocopy must be on plain white paper.\n        *   Do not reduce the image size.\n        *   Single-sided.\n    *   **Passport Photo:**\n        *   One color photo is required.\n        *   The photo must be:\n            *   2 x 2 inches (51 x 51 mm) in size\n            *   Taken within the last 6 months\n            *   Taken in front of a plain white or off-white background\n            *   Full face, front view with a neutral facial expression or natural smile, and both eyes open\n            *   Properly sized (head must be between 1 inch and 1 1/8 inches from the bottom of the chin to the top of the head)\n            *   Printed on matte or glossy photo-quality paper\n            *   Not digitally altered or retouched.\n        *   Many drugstores, pharmacies, and shipping stores offer passport photo services.\n\n4.  **Pay the Fees:** Passport fees vary depending on the type of application, whether you want a passport book or a passport card (or both), and whether you want expedited service.  Check the current fees on the Department of State's website (travel.state.gov).\n\n    *   **How to pay:**\n        *   **In person:** Check the payment options accepted by the acceptance facility you are using. Many accept credit cards, debit cards, checks, and money orders.\n        *   **By mail (for renewals using Form DS-82):** Check or money order payable to \"U.S. Department of State.\"  Do *not* send cash.\n\n5.  **Submit Your Application:** Where you submit your application depends on your situation:\n\n    *   **Form DS-11 (First-time applicants, those under 16, etc.):  Must apply in person.**  You have two options:\n        *   **At a passport acceptance facility:** Many post offices, clerks of court, and public libraries are designated acceptance facilities.  You can find a list of locations on the Department of State's website. You'll present your completed application, supporting documents, photo, and payment to an acceptance agent.\n        *   **At a regional passport agency:**  These agencies are located in major cities.  You *must* make an appointment to apply at a regional passport agency.  This option is usually reserved for those with urgent travel needs.  Call the National Passport Information Center to schedule an appointment.\n\n    *   **Form DS-82 (Renewals):  Can apply by mail.** Mail your completed application, previous passport, supporting documents (if applicable, such as a name change document), photo, and payment to the address specified on the form instructions.\n\n    *   **Form DS-5504 (Corrections, Name Changes within 1 year):**  Follow the instructions on the form. It's typically submitted by mail, but in certain cases, you may need to apply in person.\n\n**Important Considerations & Tips:**\n\n*   **Processing Times:** Processing times vary.  Check the current processing times on the Department of State's website before applying.  You can pay for expedited service for faster processing, but even then, there's no guarantee.  Plan well in advance of your travel dates.\n\n*   **Minors:**  Special rules apply to passport applications for children under 16.  Generally, both parents or legal guardians must appear in person with the child.  If one parent cannot appear, they must provide a notarized statement of consent.  More information is available on the Department of State's website.  Children 16 and 17 still require parental awareness.\n\n*   **Lost or Stolen Passports:** Report a lost or stolen passport immediately to the Department of State to prevent identity theft. You can report it online or by phone. You will then need to apply for a replacement passport using Form DS-11.\n\n*   **Name Changes:** If you have changed your name, you will need to provide documentation of the name change, such as a marriage certificate or court order.  If you changed your name more than one year after your passport was issued, you must use form DS-11 and apply in person.\n\n*   **Expedited Service:** Expedited service costs an additional fee and reduces processing time. You can also pay for 1-2 day delivery of your passport once it's issued. Expedited processing can be selected whether applying in person or via mail.\n\n*   **Travel Advisories:** Before traveling, check the State Department's travel advisories for your destination.\n\n*   **Contact Information:**\n\n    *   **National Passport Information Center:**  1-877-487-2778 (toll-free)\n    *   **Website:** travel.state.gov\n\n**In Summary (Simplified):**\n\n1.  **Choose the correct form (DS-11, DS-82, or DS-5504) based on your situation.**\n2.  **Complete the form accurately.**\n3.  **Gather your proof of citizenship, proof of identity, and passport photo.**\n4.  **Pay the required fees.**\n5.  **Submit your application (in person at an acceptance facility or regional agency, or by mail, depending on the form).**\n\nThe best way to ensure a smooth passport application process is to visit the U.S. Department of State's website (travel.state.gov) and carefully read the instructions for the specific form you are using.  Good luck!\n",
